Nevada ([/nəˈvædə/](/Help:IPA/English) nə-VAD-ə; [5] [6] Spanish: [neˈβaða] [/Help:IPA/Spanish]) is a landlocked [state](/U.S._state) in the [Western United States](/Western_United_States). It’s sometimes lumped into the [Mountain West](/Mountain_States) or even the [Southwestern United States](/Southwestern_United_States), because geography can be so… fluid. It borders [Oregon](/Oregon) to the northwest, [Idaho](/Idaho) to the northeast, [California](/California) to the west, [Arizona](/Arizona) to the southeast, and [Utah](/Utah) to the east. Nevada is the [seventh-most extensive](/List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_area), the [32nd-most populous](/List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_population), and, mercifully, the [ninth-least densely populated](/List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_population_density) U.S. state. Nearly three-quarters of its population huddles in [Clark County](/Clark_County,_Nevada), which contains the [Las Vegas–Paradise metropolitan area](/Las_Vegas_Valley), home to three of the state's four largest incorporated cities. [7] Nevada's capital is [Carson City](/Carson_City,_Nevada). [Las Vegas](/Las_Vegas), predictably, is the largest city. Nevada is also the westernmost [U.S. state without coastline](/List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_coastline) and, if you’re counting first-level administrative divisions, the westernmost landlocked one in the [Americas](/Americas).

They call it the "Silver State," and they’re not wrong. Silver practically defined its history and economy. It’s also the "Battle Born State," a nod to its admission to the Union during the [Civil War](/American_Civil_War) – a phrase that’s even emblazoned on [its state flag](/Flag_of_Nevada). Apparently, [Abraham Lincoln](/Abraham_Lincoln) found the infusion of nearly $400 million in silver from the [Comstock Lode](/Comstock_Lode) to be quite beneficial for the Union cause. [9] It’s also known as the "[Sagebrush](/Sagebrush) State," for the ubiquitous plant, and the "[Sage-hen](/Sage_grouse) State," though I suspect the former is more accurate. The name itself, "Nevada," is Spanish for "snowy," a reference to the winter-capped mountains that help make Nevada one of the [highest US states by mean altitude](/List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_elevation). Think the [Carson Range](/Carson_Range) (part of the [Sierra Nevada](/Sierra_Nevada), holding about a third of [Lake Tahoe](/Lake_Tahoe)), the [Toiyabe Range](/Toiyabe_Range), the [Ruby Mountains](/Ruby_Mountains), and the [Spring Mountains](/Spring_Mountains) in the south – these are the [sky islands](/Sky_island) of the [Great Basin montane forests](/Great_Basin_montane_forests). Nevada is brutally dry, sitting in the [rain shadow](/Rain_shadow) of the Sierra Nevada and basking in some of the highest [solar irradiance](/Solar_irradiance) in the country. It's mostly [desert](/Desert) and [semi-arid](/Semi-arid_climate), encompassing the majority of the [Great Basin](/Great_Basin) and a significant chunk of the [Mojave Desert](/Mojave_Desert). In 2020, a staggering 80.1% of its land was federally managed, civilian or military. [11]

The original inhabitants were [Native Americans](/Native_Americans_in_the_United_States) of the [Paiute](/Paiute), [Shoshone](/Shoshone), and [Washoe](/Washoe_people) tribes. The Spanish were the first Europeans to poke around, calling it Nevada for the snowy mountains, much like their own [Sierra Nevada in Spain](/Sierra_Nevada_(Spain)). It was part of [Alta California](/Alta_California) and [Nuevo México](/Santa_Fe_de_Nuevo_M%C3%A9xico) within the [Viceroyalty of New Spain](/Viceroyalty_of_New_Spain), eventually gaining independence as Mexico in 1821. The U.S. snagged it in 1848 after the [Mexican–American War](/Mexican%E2%80%93American_War), doling it out to the [New Mexico Territory](/New_Mexico_Territory) and [Utah Territory](/Utah_Territory) in 1850. Then, in 1859, someone struck silver at the [Comstock Lode](/Comstock_Lode). Boom. This led to enough people showing up to warrant the creation of [Nevada Territory](/Nevada_Territory) out of western Utah in 1861. Nevada officially joined the Union as the 36th state on October 31, 1864, one of only two states admitted during the Civil War (the other being [West Virginia](/West_Virginia)).

Nevada is known for its… *flexible* laws. In 1940, with a population barely nudging 110,000, it was the least populated state by a significant margin. [13] But then came legalized [gambling](/Gambling_in_the_United_States) and famously lenient marriage and divorce laws, transforming it into a tourist magnet by the 20th century. [14] [15] It’s the only U.S. state where [prostitution](/Prostitution_in_Nevada) is technically legal, though not in its most populated areas – Clark County (home to Las Vegas), [Washoe County](/Washoe_County,_Nevada) (Reno), and Carson City. The tourism industry remains its primary employer, [16] but mining is still a major player; Nevada is the fourth-largest gold producer globally. [17]

The state is grappling with increasingly frequent and severe [droughts](/Drought), exacerbated by [climate change](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Climate_change). [18] This puts a considerable strain on its [water security](/Water_security). Yet, Nevada is also surprisingly progressive in its climate change adaptation, with research at the [Desert Research Institute](/Desert_Research_Institute), extensive [water recycling](/Reclaimed_water) in the Las Vegas area, voter-mandated investment in [solar power](/Solar_power_in_Nevada), a burgeoning [electric vehicle](/Electric_vehicle) manufacturing ecosystem, and the development of the largest [lithium mine](/Thacker_Pass_lithium_mine) in the U.S. for battery production.

Etymology

The name "Nevada" is derived from the Spanish adjective *nevada* ([neˈβaða] [/Help:IPA/Spanish]), meaning "snowy" or "snow-covered." [19] The state inherited its name from the [Nevada Territory](/Nevada_Territory), which was itself named for the [Sierra Nevada](/Sierra_Nevada). [20]

Standard pronunciation

Nevadans, bless their hearts, pronounce the second syllable with the "a" of "apple" ([nəˈvædə] [/Help:IPA/English]). Some outsiders, however, insist on the "a" of "palm" ([nəˈvɑːdə] [/Help:IPA/English]). While the latter might be closer to the Spanish pronunciation (Spanish /a/ is [open central](/Open_central_unrounded_vowel) [ä], [22] whereas American English /ɑː/ can vary), [23] it's not what the locals do. State Assemblyman [Harry Mortenson](/Harry_Mortenson) even tried to get a bill passed to recognize this alternative pronunciation, but it went nowhere. The Nevadan pronunciation is what the state legislature prefers. For a while, the state's tourism board, TravelNevada, even styled it as "Nevăda" with a [breve](/Breve) over the 'a' – a design available on license plates until 2007. [26]

History

