Indigenous history

Before any Europeans showed up, the land was home to Indigenous tribes like the [Goshute](/Goshute), [Southern Paiute](/Southern_Paiute_people), [Mohave](/Mohave_people), and Wašišiw ([Washoe people](/Washoe_people)). [27] [28]

Before 1861

• Main articles: [The Californias § History](/The_Californias), and [Alta California](/Alta_California)
• Further information: [Treaty of Córdoba](/Treaty_of_C%C3%B3rdoba), [Declaration of Independence of the Mexican Empire](/Declaration_of_Independence_of_the_Mexican_Empire), [First Mexican Empire](/First_Mexican_Empire), [Provisional Government of Mexico](/Provisional_Government_of_Mexico), [First Mexican Republic](/First_Mexican_Republic), [Centralist Republic of Mexico](/Centralist_Republic_of_Mexico), [Siete Leyes](/Siete_Leyes), and [Definitive treaty of peace and friendship between Mexico and Spain](/Definitive_treaty_of_peace_and_friendship_between_Mexico_and_Spain)

Mexico in 1824. [Alta California](/Alta_California) included today's Nevada.

[Francisco Garcés](/Francisco_Garc%C3%A9s) was the first European to venture into the area. [29] Nevada was claimed as part of the [Spanish Empire](/Spanish_Empire) in the northwestern reaches of [New Spain](/New_Spain). Administratively, it fell under the [Commandancy General of the Provincias Internas](/Provincias_Internas) within the Viceroyalty of New Spain. When [the Californias](/The_Californias) were divided in 1804, Nevada became part of the [Alta California](/Alta_California) province. After Mexico won its independence in 1821, Alta California became a Mexican territory (state) with a sparse population.

[Jedediah Smith](/Jedediah_Smith) blazed a trail into the [Las Vegas Valley](/Las_Vegas_Valley) in 1827. [Peter Skene Ogden](/Peter_Skene_Ogden) navigated the [Humboldt River](/Humboldt_River) in 1828. In 1829, a merchant from [Nuevo México](/Santa_Fe_de_Nuevo_M%C3%A9xico), [Antonio Armijo](/Antonio_Armijo), streamlined travel along the [Old Spanish Trail](/Old_Spanish_Trail_(trade_route)). His scout, [Raphael Rivera](/Raphael_Rivera), was the first to name Las Vegas in an official report in 1830 to governor [José Antonio Chaves](/Jos%C3%A9_Antonio_Chaves), noting a spring in the area. [John C. Frémont](/John_C._Fr%C3%A9mont) camped at [Las Vegas Springs](/Las_Vegas_Springs) in 1844, marking the location on his expedition's map. In 1847, Mormons established the [State of Deseret](/State_of_Deseret), claiming all of Nevada within the Great Basin and Colorado watershed. They founded [Mormon Station](/Genoa,_Nevada) (now Genoa) in 1851, their first permanent settlement in what is now Nevada. Additionally, in June 1855, William Bringhurst and 29 missionaries built the first permanent structure, a 150-foot square [adobe fort](/Old_Las_Vegas_Mormon_Fort_State_Historic_Park), near downtown Las Vegas, connecting to the Spanish and [Mormon Roads](/Mormon_Road). This fort remained under [Salt Lake City](/Salt_Lake_City)'s administration until the winter of 1858–1859. Salt Lake City and [Santa Fe](/Santa_Fe,_New_Mexico) traders continued to dominate the route.

These pioneers essentially laid the groundwork for the first settlements between the [Sierra Nevadas](/Sierra_Nevada) and [Mojave Desert](/Mojave_Desert), and within the Las Vegas Valley. The cultural influence of [New Mexico](/New_Mexico) and [Utah](/Utah) is still palpable, woven into Nevada's identity through [New Mexican cuisine](/New_Mexican_cuisine) and [Mormon foodways](/Mormon_foodways), as well as [New Mexican](/New_Mexico_music) and [Mormon folk musics](/Mormon_folk_music).

The [Mexican–American War](/Mexican%E2%80%93American_War) concluded with the [Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo](/Treaty_of_Guadalupe_Hidalgo) in 1848, ceding Alta California to the United States. These new territories were initially administered as part of the [Utah Territory](/Utah_Territory) and [New Mexico Territory](/New_Mexico_Territory). The [California Gold Rush](/California_Gold_Rush) brought more people through the area via the [Emigrant Trails](/Emigrant_Trail), contributing to the [state's area evolving](/Territorial_evolution_of_Nevada). Eventually, the [Nevada Territory](/Nevada_Territory) was carved out on March 2, 1861, named after the [Sierra Nevada](/Sierra_Nevada_(U.S.))). [30]

Sculpture representing a steam locomotive, in Ely, Nevada. Early locomotives played an important part in Nevada's mining industry.

The first significant discovery of [silver ore](/Silver_ore) in the U.S. occurred in the [Comstock Lode](/Comstock_Lode) near [Virginia City, Nevada](/Virginia_City,_Nevada), in 1859.

Separation from Utah Territory

• Main articles: [Utah Territory](/Utah_Territory), [Organic act § List of organic acts](/Organic_act), [Nevada Territory](/Nevada_Territory), and [Nevada in the American Civil War](/Nevada_in_the_American_Civil_War)

Nevada territory in 1861

The Nevada Territory officially separated from Utah Territory on March 2, 1861, adopting its current name, a shortened version of *The Sierra Nevada* (Spanish for "snow-covered mountain range"). The 1861 southern boundary is still marked by [Nevada Historical Markers](/Nevada_Historical_Markers) 57 and 58 in [Lincoln](/Lincoln_County,_Nevada) and [Nye](/Nye_County,_Nevada) counties.

Statehood (1864)

• Main articles: [Admission to the Union](/Admission_to_the_Union), [List of U.S. states by date of admission to the Union](/List_of_U.S._states_by_date_of_admission_to_the_Union), [Nevada in the American Civil War](/Nevada_in_the_American_Civil_War), and [Constitution of Nevada](/Constitution_of_Nevada)

Map of the States of California and Nevada by SB Linton, 1876

Nevada officially became the 36th state just eight days before the [presidential election of 1864](/1864_United_States_presidential_election). This was unusual, as it didn't meet the typical 60,000-resident requirement set by [Congress](/United_States_Congress). [31] At the time, Nevada's population was barely over 40,000. [32] Governor [James W. Nye](/James_W._Nye) was apparently quite eager, as previous attempts to send the constitution had failed. On October 26, the full text was transmitted via telegraph at a considerable cost of $4,303.27 [33] [c] – the most expensive single telegraph dispatch on record, equating to about $86,514.04 in today's money. The response arrived on October 31, 1864: "the pain is over, the child is born, Nevada this day was admitted into the Union." This expedited admission was timed to bolster [Abraham Lincoln](/Abraham_Lincoln)'s reelection chances and ensure [Republican](/United_States_Republican_Party) dominance post-Civil War, given Nevada's mining-based economy's alignment with the Union. As it turned out, Lincoln and the Republicans won handily and didn't strictly *need* Nevada's vote, but they got it nonetheless.

Nevada is one of only two states that significantly expanded its borders after joining the Union, the other being [Missouri](/Missouri) (which gained territory via the [Platte Purchase](/Platte_Purchase)). In 1866, Nevada absorbed more of western Utah Territory, establishing its current eastern boundary. It reached its present southern boundaries on January 18, 1867, when it annexed the portion of [Pah-Ute County](/Pah-Ute_County,_Arizona) in the [Arizona Territory](/Arizona_Territory) that lay west of the Colorado River, essentially all of present-day southern Nevada. This was partly driven by the discovery of gold in the area, with officials believing Nevada could better manage the anticipated population surge. This acquisition includes all of modern [Clark County](/Clark_County,_Nevada) and the southernmost parts of [Esmeralda](/Esmeralda_County,_Nevada), Lincoln, and Nye counties. [35]

Bottle house in the mining ghost town of [Rhyolite](/Rhyolite,_Nevada); built in 1906 with about 50,000 bottles [36]

Mining was the engine of Nevada's economy for years (see [Silver mining in Nevada](/Silver_mining_in_Nevada)). When [Mark Twain](/Mark_Twain) documented his time there in [Roughing It](/Roughing_It), mining was synonymous with speculation and immense wealth. The late 19th century saw a decline in both mining and population. However, the discovery of rich silver veins in [Tonopah](/Tonopah,_Nevada) in 1900, followed by strikes in [Goldfield](/Goldfield,_Nevada) and [Rhyolite](/Rhyolite,_Nevada), ignited a second mining boom and revitalized Nevada's population.

Gambling and labor

While unregulated [gambling](/Gambling) was rampant in early Nevada mining towns, it was outlawed nationwide in 1909. The subsequent economic downturns during the [Great Depression](/Great_Depression), coupled with declining mining output and a weakened agricultural sector, prompted Nevada to re-legalize gambling on March 19, 1931, via legislative approval. Governor [Fred B. Balzar](/Fred_B._Balzar) signed this into law, alongside equally liberal divorce laws. These reforms arrived just eight days after the federal government awarded the construction contract for Boulder Dam (now [Hoover Dam](/Hoover_Dam)). [37]

Nuclear testing

The [Nevada Test Site](/Nevada_Test_Site), located about 65 miles (105 km) northwest of Las Vegas, was established on January 11, 1951, for the testing of [nuclear weapons](/Nuclear_weapons). It covers approximately 1,350 square miles (3,500 km 2 ) of desert and mountainous terrain. [Nuclear testing](/Nuclear_test) commenced with a 1-kiloton bomb detonated at [Frenchman Flat](/Frenchman_Flat) on January 27, 1951. The last atmospheric test occurred on July 17, 1962, and underground testing continued until September 23, 1992. This site holds the distinction of having the highest concentration of nuclear detonations in the U.S.

Over 80% of the state's land is federally owned. This is largely due to the arid conditions making large homesteads impractical for agriculture. Early settlers typically claimed land around water sources and then utilized the adjacent public land for grazing. This [ranching](/Ranching) model persists.

2020s

The [COVID-19 pandemic](/COVID-19_pandemic) reached Nevada on March 5, 2020. Governor [Steve Sisolak](/Steve_Sisolak) declared a [state of emergency](/State_of_emergency) on March 12, 2020, due to concerns about the virus. The state reported its first death four days later. On March 17, 2020, Sisolak ordered the closure of non-essential businesses to curb the spread.

Protests against the shutdown order began in April 2020. Nevada initiated its reopening phases on May 9, 2020, allowing businesses like restaurants, retailers, outdoor malls, and hair salons to operate with capacity limits. Phase two began on May 29, 2020, permitting the reopening of [state parks](/List_of_Nevada_state_parks) and establishments such as bars, gyms, and movie theaters. Casinos began welcoming patrons again on June 4, 2020.

