Flora and fauna

• Main article: [Fauna of Nevada](/Fauna_of_Nevada)

Nevada's vegetation is varied and changes depending on the region. It encompasses six [biotic zones](/Biotic_zone): [alpine](/Alpine_vegetation), [sub-alpine](/Sub-alpine), [ponderosa pine](/Ponderosa_pine_forest), [pinion-juniper](/Pinyon-juniper_woodland), [sagebrush](/Sagebrush), and [creosotebush](/Creosotebush). [42]

Counties

• Further information: [List of counties in Nevada](/List_of_counties_in_Nevada)

The [Las Vegas Strip](/Las_Vegas_Strip) looking South
[Carson City Mint](/Carson_City_Mint) in [Carson City](/Carson_City,_Nevada). Carson City is an [independent city](/Independent_city_(United_States)) and the capital of Nevada.

Nevada is organized into political divisions known as [counties](/County_(United_States)). Carson City is a consolidated municipality, functioning as both a city and a county. As of 1919, there were 17 counties, ranging in size from 146 to 18,159 square miles (380 to 47,030 km 2 ).

[Lake County](/Lake_County,_Nevada), one of the original nine counties established in 1861, was renamed [Roop County](/Roop_County,_Nevada) in 1862. Part of this county was ceded to [Lassen County, California](/Lassen_County,_California) in 1864, resolving border disputes. In 1883, Washoe County absorbed the remaining Nevada portion. [43]

In 1969, Ormsby County was dissolved and replaced by the [Consolidated Municipality of Carson City](/Consolidated_Municipality_of_Carson_City), established by the Legislature with the same boundaries.

[Bullfrog County](/Bullfrog_County,_Nevada) was created in 1987 from a section of Nye County. However, its creation was deemed unconstitutional and the county was abolished in 1989. [43]

Humboldt County was initially designated in 1856 by the [Utah Territorial Legislature](/Utah_Territorial_Legislature) and re-established in 1861 by the new Nevada Legislature.

Clark County is the most populous in Nevada, housing nearly three-quarters of its residents. Las Vegas, the state's largest city, has served as the [county seat](/County_seat) since the county's formation in 1909 from a portion of [Lincoln County, Nevada](/Lincoln_County,_Nevada). Prior to this, it was part of Arizona Territory. Clark County attracts millions of tourists annually; an estimated 44 million visited in 2014. [44]

Washoe County is the second most populous county in Nevada, with its county seat in [Reno](/Reno,_Nevada). It encompasses the [Reno–Sparks metropolitan area](/Reno%E2%80%93Sparks_metropolitan_area).

Lyon County ranks third in population. Established in 1861, it was named in honor of [Nathaniel Lyon](/Nathaniel_Lyon), the first Union General killed in the [Civil War](/American_Civil_War). Its current county seat is [Yerington](/Yerington,_Nevada). The initial county seat was established in [Dayton](/Dayton,_Nevada) on November 29, 1861. [45]

