As of 2011, 63.6% of Nevada's population under the age of one were minorities. [69] Las Vegas is considered a [majority-minority](/Majority-minority) city. According to U.S. Census Bureau estimates from July 1, 2018, non-Hispanic Whites comprised 48.7% of Nevada's population. [70]

In [Douglas](/Douglas_County,_Nevada), [Mineral](/Mineral_County,_Nevada), and [Pershing](/Pershing_County,_Nevada) counties, residents of Mexican ancestry form a plurality. [Nye County](/Nye_County,_Nevada) and [Humboldt County](/Humboldt_County,_Nevada) have a majority of residents of German ancestry, while [Washoe County](/Washoe_County,_Nevada) has a significant Irish American population. Americans of English descent are the plurality in [Lincoln County](/Lincoln_County,_Nevada), [Churchill County](/Churchill_County,_Nevada), [Lyon County](/Lyon_County,_Nevada), [White Pine County](/White_Pine_County,_Nevada), and [Eureka County](/Eureka_County,_Nevada).

Asian Americans have been present in Nevada since at least the 1850s, when the [California gold rush](/California_gold_rush) drew thousands of Chinese miners to Washoe County. They were followed by Japanese farmworkers in the late 19th century. By the late 20th century, immigrants from China, Japan, Korea, the [Philippines](/Philippines), [Bangladesh](/Bangladesh), India, and [Vietnam](/Vietnam) had established communities in the Las Vegas metropolitan area. The city now boasts a substantial Asian American population, with a predominantly Chinese and [Taiwanese](/Taiwanese_American) area known as "[Chinatown](/Chinatown,_Las_Vegas)" west of I-15 on Spring Mountain Road. [Filipino Americans](/Filipino_Americans) represent the largest Asian American group in the state, numbering over 202,000, accounting for 59.8% of the Asian American population in Nevada and approximately 6.4% of the state's total population. [71]

Mining booms attracted numerous Greek and Eastern European immigrants to Nevada. [72] In the early 20th century, [Greeks](/Greeks), [Slavs](/Slavs), [Danes](/Danes), [Japanese](/Japanese_people), [Italians](/Italians), and [Basques](/Basque_Americans_in_Nevada) migrated to Nevada. [73] [Chileans](/Chilean_Americans) were present in the state as early as 1870. [74] During the mid-1800s, a considerable number of European immigrants, primarily from [Ireland](/Ireland), [England](/England), and [Germany](/Germany), arrived seeking opportunities in the region's burgeoning mining sector. [75]

The primary Native American tribes in Nevada historically include the [Northern](/Northern_Paiute) and [Southern Paiute](/Southern_Paiute_people), [Western Shoshone](/Western_Shoshone), [Goshute](/Goshute), [Hualapai](/Hualapai), [Washoe](/Washoe_people), and [Ute](/Ute_people) tribes. [76]

Whites remain the largest racial or ethnic group in Nevada. [77] Hispanics are the fastest-growing ethnic group in the state. [78] There is a significant and growing population of people from Mexico, Guatemala, and El Salvador in Nevada. [79] Nevada also has a rapidly expanding multiracial population. [80]

The leading countries of origin for immigrants in Nevada are [Mexico](/Mexico) (39.5% of immigrants), the [Philippines](/Philippines) (14.3%), [El Salvador](/El_Salvador) (5.2%), [China](/China) (3.1%), and [Cuba](/Cuba) (3%). [81]

The majority of Nevada's population is of white (European) ancestry. A small segment traces its roots to Basque individuals recruited as sheepherders. Hispanics in Nevada are primarily of Mexican and Cuban heritage, constituting about one-fourth of the state's residents and concentrated in the southeast. African Americans are mainly found in the Las Vegas and Reno areas, making up less than one-tenth of the population. Native Americans from the Paiute, Shoshone, and Washoe tribes reside on several reservations across the state and represent a small fraction of Nevada's population. [82]

The most common ancestries reported in Nevada include Mexican, German, Irish, English, Italian, and various Asian origins. [83]

Nevada ranks as the third most diverse state in the country, surpassed only by Hawaii and California. [84] [85]

