Infrastructure

Transportation

State route shield
[U.S. Route 50](/U.S._Route_50_in_Nevada), also known as "The Loneliest Road in America"

[Amtrak](/Amtrak)'s [California Zephyr](/California_Zephyr) train operates daily between Chicago and [Emeryville, California](/Emeryville,_California), serving [Elko](/Elko,_Nevada), [Winnemucca](/Winnemucca,_Nevada), and Reno along the original Union Pacific [transcontinental railroad](/Transcontinental_railroad) line. Las Vegas has lacked passenger train service since the discontinuation of Amtrak's [Desert Wind](/Desert_Wind) in 1997. [Amtrak Thruway](/Amtrak_Thruway) buses connect Las Vegas to trains at [Needles, California](/Needles,_California), Los Angeles, and [Bakersfield, California](/Bakersfield,_California); and Stateline, Nevada, to [Sacramento, California](/Sacramento,_California). Several proposals exist for restoring service to Los Angeles, with the privately operated [Brightline West](/Brightline_West) commencing construction in 2024.

The [Union Pacific Railroad](/Union_Pacific_Railroad) operates rail lines in northern and southern Nevada. [Greyhound Lines](/Greyhound_Lines) provides some intercity bus service.

[Interstate 15](/Interstate_15_in_Nevada) (I-15) traverses the southern tip of the state, connecting Las Vegas and other communities. [I-215](/Interstate_215_(Nevada)) and [I-515](/Interstate_515) serve the Las Vegas metropolitan area. [I-80](/Interstate_80_in_Nevada) crosses northern Nevada, roughly following the Humboldt River eastward from Utah and the Truckee River westward through Reno into California. It includes a spur route, [I-580](/Interstate_580_(Nevada)). Nevada is also served by U.S. Highways: [US 6](/U.S._Route_6_in_Nevada), [US 50](/U.S._Route_50_in_Nevada), [US 93](/U.S._Route_93_in_Nevada), [US 95](/U.S._Route_95_in_Nevada), and [US 395](/U.S._Route_395_in_Nevada). The state maintains 189 [Nevada state routes](/List_of_state_routes_in_Nevada). Many counties also have county routes, though they are often unsigned or unpaved in rural areas. Nevada is one of the few states lacking a continuous [interstate highway](/Interstate_highway) connecting its two major population centers; the route between Las Vegas and Reno involves a combination of Interstates and U.S. Highways. The proposed [Interstate 11](/Interstate_11) may eventually address this. [121]

The state permits [semi-trailer trucks](/Semi-trailer_truck) with three trailers, often referred to as "[road trains](/Road_train)" in Australia, though typically smaller in the U.S. due to the need to navigate steep mountain passes.

[RTC Transit](/RTC_Transit) operates public transportation in the Las Vegas metropolitan area, serving as the state's largest transit agency. Its bus network covers the [Las Vegas Valley](/Las_Vegas_Valley), including [The Deuce](/The_Deuce_(transit_bus_service)), a [double-decker bus](/Double-decker_bus) service on the [Las Vegas Strip](/Las_Vegas_Strip), and various outlying routes. RTC RIDE provides local bus service throughout the Reno-Sparks metropolitan area. Other transit systems include Carson City's JAC. Most other counties lack public transportation.

Additionally, a 4-mile (6.4 km) [monorail](/Monorail) system serves the Las Vegas area. The [Las Vegas Monorail](/Las_Monorail) line connects several casino properties and the [Las Vegas Convention Center](/Las_Vegas_Convention_Center) east of the Strip, running near Paradise Road, with potential future extensions to [Harry Reid International Airport](/Harry_Reid_International_Airport). Some hotels also operate short monorail lines connecting their properties.

Harry Reid International Airport in Las Vegas is the busiest airport serving Nevada. [Reno-Tahoe International Airport](/Reno-Tahoe_International_Airport) (formerly Reno Cannon International Airport) is the state's other major airport.

Energy

• See also: [List of power stations in Nevada](/List_of_power_stations_in_Nevada)
• External image [Map of Nevada electricity grid](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2f/Nevada_Electricity_Grid_Map.svg/320px-Nevada_Electricity_Grid_Map.svg.png)

Nevada has a robust [solar energy sector](/Solar_power_in_Nevada). A 2013 study indicated solar users provided a net benefit of $36 million. However, in December 2015, the Public Utility Commission allowed NV Energy, the state's sole power company, to impose higher rates and fees on solar users, leading to a sharp decline in rooftop solar installations. [122]

In December 1987, Congress designated the [Yucca Mountain nuclear waste repository](/Yucca_Mountain_nuclear_waste_repository) as the sole site for characterization as a permanent repository for the nation's [highly radioactive waste](/Highly_radioactive_waste). [123]

Affordable housing

In 2018, the [National Low Income Housing Coalition](/National_Low_Income_Housing_Coalition) reported that Nevada had only 15 affordable rental homes available per 100 extremely low-income (ELI) households, indicating a significant shortage of 71,358 affordable rental homes. [124] This deficit was exacerbated by the [Great Recession](/Great_Recession) and the 2007-2008 housing crisis. Since then, rising housing prices and increased demand have outpaced supply. Low-income service workers are increasingly displaced by an influx of tech professionals. In Nevada, affording a [single-family home](/Single-family_detached_home) typically requires a six-figure income, which is beyond the reach of the average [salary](/List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_median_wage_and_mean_wage) of $54,842 per year. [125] [126] Consequently, 112,872 renters dedicate over half their annual income to housing costs. [127]

Affordability is defined as spending 30% or less of income on housing. The gap between housing costs and income remains substantial. Renters are seeking solutions, leading to shared housing arrangements or relocation to areas further from metropolitan centers. One proposed solution involves increasing the supply of higher-income jobs, requiring Nevadans to retrain for new careers.

Education

• See also: [List of high schools in Nevada](/List_of_high_schools_in_Nevada) and [List of school districts in Nevada](/List_of_school_districts_in_Nevada)

Nevada's educational system comprises public and private [elementary](/Elementary_school), [middle](/Middle_school), and [high schools](/High_school_(North_America)), alongside colleges and universities.

A May 2015 educational reform law expanded school choice options for approximately 450,000 Nevada students at or below 185% of the [federal poverty level](/Federal_poverty_level). This legislation enables Education Savings Accounts (ESAs) to fund private school tuition, textbooks, and tutoring. [128] [129]

Approximately 86.9% of Nevada residents have earned a high school diploma or equivalent, falling slightly below the national average of 88.6%. [130]

