State politics

Party Registration by County in Nevada (February 2025):
• Republican ≥ 30%
• Republican ≥ 40%
• Republican ≥ 50%
• Republican ≥ 60%
• Unaffiliated ≥ 30%

Rapid growth in the southern part of the state has created a distinct political divide between northern and southern Nevada. Historically, northern Nevada has leaned heavily [Republican](/Republican_Party_(United_States)), with its rural counties being among the most conservative regions. Carson City, the state capital, is a Republican-leaning swing city/county. Washoe County, home to Reno, has traditionally been strongly Republican but has become a more balanced swing county, mirroring the state's overall trend. Clark County, the domain of Las Vegas, has been a Democratic stronghold since its founding in 1909, having voted Republican only six times (once for a third-party candidate). However, it has become more competitive recently, notably in the 2024 Presidential Election where the Democratic margin was a narrow 2.63 percentage points. [154] Clark and Washoe counties have long dominated state politics, accounting for 87% of Nevada's votes and electing a substantial majority of the state legislature. The last Republican to win Clark County was [George H. W. Bush](/George_H._W._Bush) in 1988, and the last to win Washoe County was [George W. Bush](/George_W._Bush) in 2004. The vast majority of elected officials originate from either Las Vegas or Reno. [155] Donald Trump managed to secure a statewide majority in Nevada in 2024, despite losing both Clark and Washoe counties.

In 2014, Republican [Adam Laxalt](/Adam_Laxalt), despite losing Clark and Washoe counties, was elected [Attorney General](/Nevada_Attorney_General). His losses in those counties were relatively narrow: 5.6% in Clark and 1.4% in Washoe, attributed to lower turnout.

National politics

• See also: [United States presidential elections in Nevada](/United_States_presidential_elections_in_Nevada)

[2024 U.S. presidential election results](/2024_United_States_presidential_election_in_Nevada) by county in Nevada
• Democratic
• Republican

Nevada has historically voted with the winner in nearly every presidential election since its statehood in 1864, only deviating eight times, mostly before 1900. Since 1912, it has been a consistent bellwether, siding with the presidential victor in 27 out of 29 elections. The exceptions were [1976](/1976_United_States_presidential_election), when it backed [Gerald Ford](/Gerald_Ford) over [Jimmy Carter](/Jimmy_Carter), and [2016](/2016_United_States_presidential_election), when [Hillary Clinton](/Hillary_Clinton) carried the state against [Donald Trump](/Donald_Trump). In the [1960](/1960_United_States_presidential_election) election, it was one of only three states in the [American West](/Western_United_States) won by [John F. Kennedy](/John_F._Kennedy), albeit narrowly. [157]
Nevada's current U.S. Senators are Democrats [Catherine Cortez Masto](/Catherine_Cortez_Masto) and [Jacky Rosen](/Jacky_Rosen). The governorship is held by Republican [Joe Lombardo](/Joe_Lombardo).

Elections

• Main article: [Elections in Nevada](/Elections_in_Nevada)

Nevada uniquely offers a "none of the above" option on its ballots, officially termed [None of These Candidates](/None_of_the_above). Introduced in 1975, this option appears in all statewide elections. If "None of These Candidates" receives a [plurality](/Plurality_(voting)), the candidate with the next highest vote total wins. [158]

A 2020 study ranked Nevada 23rd on the "Cost of Voting Index," measuring the ease of voting across U.S. states. [159]

Culture

Entertainment and tourism

Resort destinations such as Las Vegas, Reno, Lake Tahoe, and [Laughlin](/Laughlin,_Nevada) draw visitors globally. In fiscal year 2022, Nevada casinos reported $10.7 billion in gaming revenue and an additional $15.7 billion in non-gaming revenue. [160]

Nevada leads the nation in hotel rooms per capita. The American Hotel and Lodging Association reported 187,301 rooms in 584 hotels (with 15+ rooms). While ranking below California, Texas, Florida, and New York in total rooms due to their larger populations, Nevada has one hotel room for every 14 residents, significantly exceeding the national average of one room per 67 residents. [161]

[Prostitution is legal in select Nevada counties](/Prostitution_in_Nevada) within licensed brothels, but only in counties with populations under 400,000. Despite not being a major economic driver, employing approximately 300 women as independent contractors, it remains a visible aspect of the state. Of the 14 counties eligible to legalize prostitution, eight have done so. State law prohibits it in Clark County (Las Vegas) and Washoe County (Reno). However, prostitution is legal in Storey County, which is part of the [Reno–Sparks metropolitan area](/Reno%E2%80%93Sparks_metropolitan_area).

Sports

• See also: [Las Vegas § Sports](/Las_Vegas); [Sports in the Las Vegas metropolitan area](/Sports_in_the_Las_Vegas_metropolitan_area); [Reno, Nevada § Sports](/Reno,_Nevada); and [Henderson, Nevada § Sports](/Henderson,_Nevada)

The Las Vegas Valley is home to the [Vegas Golden Knights](/Vegas_Golden_Knights) of the [National Hockey League](/National_Hockey_League), who began play in the [2017–18 NHL season](/2017%E2%80%9318_NHL_season) at [T-Mobile Arena](/T-Mobile_Arena) on the Las Vegas Strip in [Paradise](/Paradise,_Nevada). The [Las Vegas Raiders](/Las_Vegas_Raiders) of the [National Football League](/National_Football_League) moved from Oakland, California, and began play at [Allegiant Stadium](/Allegiant_Stadium) in Paradise in 2020. The [Las Vegas Aces](/Las_Vegas_Aces) of the [WNBA](/Women%27s_National_Basketball_Association) relocated from San Antonio and started playing in 2018 at the [Mandalay Bay Events Center](/Mandalay_Bay_Events_Center). The [Oakland Athletics](/Oakland_Athletics) of [Major League Baseball](/Major_League_Baseball) plan to relocate to Las Vegas by 2027. [162] [163]

Nevada takes considerable pride in its college sports programs, particularly college football. The state's teams include the [Nevada Wolf Pack](/Nevada_Wolf_Pack) (representing the University of Nevada, Reno) and the [UNLV Rebels](/UNLV_Rebels) (representing the University of Nevada, Las Vegas), both competing in the [Mountain West Conference](/Mountain_West_Conference) (MW).

UNLV's men's basketball program achieved national prominence in the late 1980s and early 1990s under coach [Jerry Tarkanian](/Jerry_Tarkanian). The Runnin' Rebels became one of the era's elite programs. In 1990, [UNLV](/1989%E2%80%9390_UNLV_Runnin%27_Rebels_basketball_team) secured the Men's Division I Championship by defeating [Duke](/1989%E2%80%9390_Duke_Blue_Devils_men%27s_basketball_team) 103–73, setting tournament records for points scored and margin of victory in the title game.

In [1991](/1990%E2%80%9391_UNLV_Runnin%27_Rebels_basketball_team), UNLV completed a regular season undefeated, a feat unmatched in Division I men's basketball for over 20 years. Forward [Larry Johnson](/Larry_Johnson_(basketball,_born_1969)) garnered numerous awards, including the [Naismith Award](/Naismith_College_Player_of_the_Year). UNLV reached the Final Four again but lost a close national semifinal 79–77 to [Duke](/1990%E2%80%9391_Duke_Blue_Devils_men%27s_basketball_team). The Runnin' Rebels held the [Associated Press](/AP_Poll) pre-season No. 1 ranking for two consecutive seasons (1989–90, 1990–91), a feat only matched by [North Carolina](/North_Carolina_Tar_Heels_men%27s_basketball) (2007–08, 2008–09).

Nevada's engagement with major college sports extends beyond its local universities. The Las Vegas area has become a significant hub for college basketball conference tournaments in the 21st century. The MW, [West Coast Conference](/West_Coast_Conference), and [Western Athletic Conference](/Western_Athletic_Conference) all hold their men's and women's tournaments there, as does the Pac-12 for its men's tournament. The [Big Sky Conference](/Big_Sky_Conference) began hosting both its men's and women's tournaments in Reno in 2016, after decades of campus-based events.

Las Vegas has hosted numerous major [professional boxing](/Professional_boxing) matches, including high-profile bouts at the [MGM Grand Garden Arena](/MGM_Grand_Garden_Arena) (e.g., [Mike Tyson vs. Evander Holyfield](/Mike_Tyson_vs._Evander_Holyfield), [Oscar De La Hoya vs. Floyd Mayweather Jr.](/Oscar_De_La_Hoya_vs._Floyd_Mayweather_Jr.)) and at the newer [T-Mobile Arena](/T-Mobile_Arena) (e.g., [Canelo Álvarez vs. Amir Khan](/Canelo_%C3%81lvarez_vs._Amir_Khan)).

With the surge in popularity of [mixed martial arts](/Mixed_martial_arts) (MMA), organizations like the [UFC](/Ultimate_Fighting_Championship) have recognized Las Vegas as a prime location for events due to its extensive venue options. The [Mandalay Bay Events Center](/Mandalay_Bay_Events_Center) and [MGM Grand Garden Arena](/MGM_Grand_Garden_Arena) are popular venues for MMA events, having hosted numerous UFC and other title fights. Las Vegas has hosted the most UFC events, with 86.

The state is also home to the [Las Vegas Motor Speedway](/Las_Vegas_Motor_Speedway), which hosts NASCAR's [Pennzoil 400](/Pennzoil_400_(Las_Vegas)) and [South Point 400](/South_Point_400). Two venues near Las Vegas host major annual [rodeo](/Rodeo) events: the [Thomas & Mack Center](/Thomas_%26_Mack_Center), originally built for UNLV basketball, hosts the [National Finals Rodeo](/National_Finals_Rodeo). The bull riding-only [Professional Bull Riders](/Professional_Bull_Riders) held its World Finals at the Thomas & Mack Center before moving to T-Mobile Arena in 2016.

Notable athletes from Nevada include tennis player [Andre Agassi](/Andre_Agassi) and baseball star [Bryce Harper](/Bryce_Harper).

